\name{ExtinctionCoefficients}
\alias{ExtinctionCoefficients}
\title{Calculate Extinction Coefficients for an Amino Acid Sequence}
\usage{
ExtinctionCoefficients(aa_sequence)
}
\arguments{
  \item{aa_sequence}{A character string representing the amino acid sequence for which the extinction coefficients will be calculated.}
}
\value{
A named vector with four elements:
\itemize{
  \item \code{Ext_Coef_paired}: The extinction coefficient when all cystines are paired.
  \item \code{Absorb_paired}: The molar absorptivity (absorbance at 280 nm per 1 mg/mL) when all cystines are paired.
  \item \code{Ext_Coef_unpaired}: The extinction coefficient when all cystines are unpaired.
  \item \code{Absorb_unpaired}: The molar absorptivity (absorbance at 280 nm per 1 mg/mL) when all cystines are unpaired.
}
}
\description{
This function calculates the extinction coefficients for an amino acid sequence. It considers the contributions of tryptophan, tyrosine, and cystine residues to the overall extinction coefficient. The function returns the extinction coefficients assuming all cystines are paired or unpaired, along with the corresponding molar absorptivity values.
}
\examples{
\dontrun{
  aa_sequence <- "ACDEFGHIKLMNPQRSTVWYCC"
  ExtinctionCoefficients(aa_sequence)
}
}
